      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Cyclooctatetraene readily reacts with potassium metal to form the stable cyclooctatetraene dianion, C<sub>8</sub>H<sub>8</sub><sup>2–</sup>. Why do you suppose this reaction occurs so easily? What geometry do you expect for the cyclooctatetraene dianion?</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaDhWIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--4492575aca2bb2c3e1c4c82d5d38e62ce6cdebc5/OChem_15_04_004.jpg\" alt=\"An 8-membered ring with four alternate double bonds reacts with two equivalents of potassium to form thje cyclooctatetraene dianion.\">",
